Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
set_macro_place_constraint(25.10)            set_macro_place_constraint(25.10)

Name
       set_macro_place_constraint - Enables you to specify the constraints for
       placing the macros and standard cells concurrently

Syntax
        set_macro_place_constraint

       [-help]

       [<array elements>]

       [-array  <array_name> [-common_hier <name>][-valid_group_orients {R0 MX
       MY}]

         [-place_order {horizontal vertical}]]

       [{-insts <string> | -all_macros } {-orientation <string>} [-common_hier
       <name>]]

       [-cells <string> {-cell_obs <string> | -track_adjustment <string>}]

       [-cpg <string>]

       [[-max_io_pin_group_keep_out {<depth_value> [<side_value>]}]

       [-forbidden_space_to_core {<unified_value> |  <horizontal_value  verti-
       cal_value>}]

       [-forbidden_space_to_macro  {<unified_value> | <horizontal_value verti-
       cal_value>}]

       [-min_space_to_core   {<unified_value>   |   <horizontal_value   verti-
       cal_value>}]

       [-min_space_to_macro   {<unified_value>   |   <horizontal_value  verti-
       cal_value>}]

       [-parallel_run_length  {<unified_value>  |   <vertical_value   horizon-
       tal_value>}]

       [-power_domain_as_core {true | false}]

       [-horizontal_stacking       {<max_macro_stack_length      min_space_be-
       tween_macro_stack max_space_between_macros>}]

       [-vertical_stacking       {<max_macro_stack_length        min_space_be-
       tween_macro_stack max_space_between_macros>}]

       [-honor_strict_spacing_constraint {true | false}]

       [-avoid_abut_macro_edge_with_pins {true | false}]

       [-same_length_site <integer>]

       [-pg_resource_model {<M1 value1 M2 value2 ...>}]

       [-macro_corner_keepout {<double_endcap_width> <double_endcap_height>}]

       [-halo_sharing {true | false}]

       [-parallel_run_length_for_stacking  {<unified_value>  | <vertical_value
       horizontal_value>}] ]

       Enables you to specify the constraints for placing the macros and stan-
       dard cells concurrently. These constraints can be used to place  macros
       in  an  array  (or  matrix)  and  define the relative placement of each
       macro. The whole array, treated like one macro, can be flipped or  mir-
       rored  (R0,  MX,  MY,  R180).  You can use the new set_macro_place_con-
       straint command to specify:

              * Macro array constraints

              * Group aligning constraints

              * Macro-to-macro and macro-to-core boundary spacing constraints

              * Macro orientation constraints

              * Over macro power routing modeling

              * Maximum stacking length

              * Reserved space for pin routing

              * I/O Pin Keep-out

       Note: For 3D designs in Integrity 3D-IC platform, each die carries  its
       own  macro  place constraint information. You must switch to a specific
       die before invoking the set_macro_place_constraint command.

Parameters
       -all_macros
              Specifies that all macros should honor  the  constraints.   This
              option makes sense when using the -orientation option.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       <array_elements>
              Specifies the instance members information of a row or column of
              the array in the following format:

              inst_name:orientation [spacing inst_name:orientation ] +

              Note:  The  <array_elements> should be specified with the -array
              parameter.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -array <array_name>
              Specifies the macro array name.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -avoid_abut_macro_edge_with_pins {true | false}
              When set to true, the  set_macro_place_constraint  command  does
              not  abut  macro  edges  with pins even if the macro distance is
              within the forbidden space setting. Macros will be separated  by
              the min_space_to_macro distance.

              Default: true

              Data_type: enum, optional

       -cell_obs {{<Layer1_Name PowerStripeWidth SpacingBetweenStripes>}
       {<Layer2_Name ....>}}
              Specifies the layer width and spacing to add cell obstruction on
              each  macro to model power stripes . During the concurrent macro
              placement the power mesh does not exist.  This parameter  allows
              to mimic the number of routing tracks occupied by the real power
              mesh  over the macros to make the congestion analysis more accu-
              rate during the concurrent macro placement.

              The format is:

              cell_obs{{<Layer1_Name PowerStripeWidth  SpacingBetweenStripes>}
              {<Layer2_Name ....>}}

              Example:

              set_macro_place_constraint  -cells  <cell_name>   -cell_obs {{M5
              0.24 1.251} {M8 0.64 8.409} {M9 1.2 7.49} }

               Note: This setting  is  generated  automatically  by  the  cre-
              ate_pg_model_for_macro_place  command.  It is highly recommended
              to use this command to define the -cell_obs parameter.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -cells <string>
              Used in combination with the -cell_obs command to specifies  the
              constraints for all instances of the specified cells.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -common_hier <name>
              Specifies  the  common  logic  hierarchy name for <inst_name> in
              <array_elements>, so  the  <inst_name>  can  be  specified  with
              short-hand format.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -cpg <string>
              Specifies the cpg guide of one instance.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -forbidden_space_to_core {<unified_value> | <horizontal_value verti-
       cal_value>}
              Specifies  the value for forbidden spacing between macro to core
              boundary. If the space between the macro  and  core  is  smaller
              than this value, then the macros are abutted.Note:

              * If  only  one  unified value is specified, both horizontal and
                vertical spacings use the same value. If two values are speci-
                fied, the first value is for the horizontal spacing, the  sec-
                ond value is for the vertical spacing.

              * In  case  the -min_space_to_core parameter has been specified,
                then the value specified for the -forbidden_space_to_core  pa-
                rameter  should  be  less  than  the  value  specified for the
                -min_space_to_core parameter.

              Minimum=0

              Maximum=100000

              Default: <0>

              Data_type: string, optional

       -forbidden_space_to_macro {<unified_value> | <horizontal_value verti-
       cal_value>}
              Specifies the value for forbidden spacing between macro to macro
              boundary. If the space between the macros is smaller  than  this
              value, then the macros are abutted.

              Note:

              * If  only  one  unified value is specified, both horizontal and
                vertical spacings use the same value. If two values are speci-
                fied, the first value is for the horizontal spacing, the  sec-
                ond value is for the vertical spacing.

              * In  case the -min_space_to_macro parameter has been specified,
                then the value specified for the -forbidden_space_to_macro pa-
                rameter should be  less  than  the  value  specified  for  the
                -min_space_to_macro parameter.

              Minimum=0

              Maximum=100000

              Default: <0>

              Data_type: string, optional

       -halo_sharing {true | false}
              When enabled, abutted macros can share halos between them.

              Note:  When the spacing between two macros is less than the for-
              bidden-space-to-macro, the two macros are abutted. Since a  sin-
              gle  halo  width  instead  of double width is enough to meet the
              physical rules, abutted macros can share halos between them  us-
              ing the new -halo_sharing parameter.

              Note:  The  halos  of  the abutted macros can overlap but macros
              cannot overlap with the halo of the other macro.

              Default: false

              Data_type: enum, optional

       -help  Outputs a brief description that includes the type  and  default
              information for each set_macro_place_constraint parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man set_macro_place_constraint

       -honor_strict_spacing_constraint{true | false}
              When  set  to  true, it specifies that the forbidden spacing and
              minimum spacing constraints must be honored strictly.

              Data_type: enum, optional

       -horizontal_stacking {<max_macro_stack_length  min_space_be-
       tween_macro_stack  max_space_between_macros>}
              Specifies the maximum horizontal stack  depth  and  the  minimum
              horizontal spacing.

              * max_macro_stack_length:  Specifies  that  the  macro  stacking
                length should not be more than the specified value.

              * min_space_between_macro_stack: Specifies the  spacing  between
                different macro stacks.

              * <max_space_between_macros>:  Specifies  the  maximum space be-
                tween macros. When the macro spacing is less than  the  speci-
                fied value, the macros are counted in the stacking length. For
                example,  if  the  max_space_between_macro value is 9 then the
                macros will be considered as packed if the space  between  the
                macros  is  between  0 and 9, however, if the real space is 10
                then nothing will happened.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -insts <string>
              Specifies the macros on which the  orientation  constraints  are
              set.   Refer to the -orientation for more information.

       -macro_corner_keepout {<double_endcap_width> <double_endcap_height>}
              Specifies  the macro corner spacing constraints. It ensures that
              there is enough space between the macro  corners  for  inserting
              the endcap cells properly.

              Note:  The corner keepout area starts at the corner of the macro
              halo.

              Note: The macro corner spacing constraints specified  with  this
              parameter    are   honored   by   the   refine_macro_place   and
              check_macro_place_constraint commands. However, if honoring  the
              corner  keepout  constraint is difficult, corner abutting is al-
              lowed.

              Note: The tool reserves either  the  horizontal  keepout  larger
              than  double  corner  cell width or vertical keepout larger than
              double corner cell height

              Default: {0,0}

              Data_type: string, optional

       -max_io_pin_group_keep_out {<depth_value> [<side_value>]}
              Specifies the maximum height and (optionally) side extension  to
              automatically add macro-only blockages to IO pins.

              Note:   The   -max_io_pin_group_keep_out parameter automatically
              coordinates the size of the macro-only blockages  based  on  the
              pin density and number for each group of IO pins.

              Note:  Side  value  is  optional. If you do not specify the side
              value, the set_macro_place_constraint command  follows  the  de-
              fault  method  to calculate the side ( side = 1/4 depth). If you
              specify the side value, the max IO group  needs  to  follow  the
              specified  depth  and side distance. The blockages of smaller IO
              groups  will  be  derived  automatically,   keeping   the   same
              <depth/side> proportion (as described for the max IO group)

              Innovus supports the following formats:

              set_macro_place_constraint            -max_io_pin_group_keep_out
              <depth_value>

              set_macro_place_constraint            -max_io_pin_group_keep_out
              {<depth_value>}

              set_macro_place_constraint            -max_io_pin_group_keep_out
              {<depth_value side_value>}

              Note:  The depth and side values are specified in microns.

              Minimum=0

              Maximum=100000

              Data_type: string, optional

       -min_space_to_core {<unified_value> | <horizontal_value verti-
       cal_value>}
              Specifies the value for the minimum spacing  between  macro  and
              core  boundary.  If  the  space  between  the  macro and core is
              smaller than this value and larger  than  the  forbidden  space,
              then the macros are pushed away from the core to minimum space.

              Note:  If  only  one unified value is specified, both horizontal
              and vertical spacings use the same  value.  If  two  values  are
              specified,  the  first  value is for the horizontal spacing, the
              second value is for the vertical spacing.

              Minimum=0

              Maximum=100000

              Default: <0>

              Data_type: string, optional

       -min_space_to_macro {<unified_value> | <horizontal_value verti-
       cal_value>}
              Specifies the value for the minimum  spacing  between  macro  to
              macro  boundary.  If  the  space between the macros is less than
              this value, then the macros are aligned.

              Note: If only one unified value is  specified,  both  horizontal
              and  vertical  spacings  use  the  same value. If two values are
              specified, the first value is for the  horizontal  spacing,  the
              second value is for the vertical spacing.

              For Example:

              * In the following command, both horizontal and vertical spacing
                use the same value.

                set_macro_place_constraint -min_space_to_macro 10

              * In  the  following  command, the first value is for horizontal
                spacing, the second value is for vertical spacing.

                set_macro_place_constraint -min_space_to_macro {10 20}

              Minimum=0

              Maximum=100000

              Data_type: string, optional

       -orientation <string>
              Specifies the allowed orientation for the macros.  The macro in-
              stances on which you want to constrain the orientations  can  be
              specified by -insts or -all_macros

              Note: Specified orientation overwrites the previous definition.

              Example:

              set_macro_place_constraint  -all_macros  -orientation  {R90 MX90
              MY90 R270}

              Data_type: string, optional

       -parallel_run_length {<unified_value> | <vertical_value horizon-
       tal_value>}
              Specifies the parallel run length  for  -min_space_to_macro  and
              -forbidden_space_to_macro  check,  only macros with parallel run
              length greater than the specified value will be checked with the
              spacing constraint.

              Note: If only one unified value is specified, the  parallel  run
              length  along  both  the vertical and horizontal directions uses
              the same value. If two values  are  specified,  then  the  first
              value  is  for the parallel run length along the vertical direc-
              tion and the second value is for the parallel run  length  along
              the horizontal direction.

              Minimum=0

              Maximum=100000

              Default: 0.000000 0.000000

              Data_type: string, optional

       -parallel_run_length_for_stacking {<unified_value> | <vertical_value
       horizontal_value>}
              Specifies  the  parallel run length for -horizontal_stacking and
              -vertical_stacking check, only  the  macros  with  parallel  run
              length  equal  to  or  greater  than the specified value will be
              counted in the stacking length.

              Note: If only one unified value is specified, the  parallel  run
              length  along  both  the vertical and horizontal directions uses
              the same value. If two values are specified then the first value
              is for the parallel run length along the vertical direction  and
              the  second value is for the parallel run length along the hori-
              zontal direction.

              Minimum=0

              Maximum=100000

              Default: 0.000000 0.000000

              Data_type: string, optional

       -pg_resource_model {<M1 value1 M2 value2 ...>}
              Specifies the pg resource model for concurrent macro  placement.
              During  the  concurrent  macro placement the power mesh does not
              exist.  This parameter allows you to mimic the number of routing
              tracks occupied by the real power mesh to  make  the  congestion
              analysis more accurate during the concurrent macro placement.

              Note:  This  setting  is  generated  automatically  by  the cre-
              ate_pg_model_for_macro_placecommand. It is highly recommended to
              use this command to define the -pg_resource_model parameter.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -place_order {horizontal | vertical}
              Specifies the place order in row (horizontal) or column  (verti-
              cal) first for macro array.

              Default: horizontal

              Data_type: enum, optional

       -power_domain_as_core {true | false}
              Specifies that the tool needs to treat the power domain boundary
              as  the  core  boundary  when  honoring certain macro place con-
              straints.   This   includes    constrains    set    using    the
              -min_space_to_core,         -forbidden_space_to_core,        and
              -avoid_abut_macro_edge_with_pins parameters.

              Note:

              * A macro outside the power domain will not be abutted  even  if
                its  space to the power domain boundary is less than the value
                for forbidden spacing between macro to core boundary (-forbid-
                den_space_to_core).

              * A macro inside the power domain will not be checked for  spac-
                ing  with other power domains or with macros outside its power
                domain.

              Default: false

              Data_type: enum, optional

       -same_length_site <integer>
              Specifies the minimum number of sites between the vertical  edge
              of two macros.

              Minimum=0

              Maximum=100000

              Data_type: int, optional

       -track_adjustment {{<layer1 density1>} {<layer2> ....}}...
              Specifies  the  layer  density  to  add track adjustment on each
              macro. For each routing layer and each macro, if the PG  density
              over  a  macro  is lower than the standard cell area then it in-
              creases the track resource in macro area to mimic the  lower  PG
              density.

              Note:  This  setting  is  generated  automatically  by  the cre-
              ate_pg_model_for_macro_place command. It is  highly  recommended
              to use this command to define the -cell_obs parameter.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -valid_group_orients {R0 MX MY}
              Specifies the valid orientations for the whole group.

              Data_type: enum, optional

       -vertical_stacking {<max_macro_stack_length min_space_be-
       tween_macro_stack max_space_between_macros>}
              Specifies  the maximum vertical stack depth and the minimum ver-
              tical spacing.

              * max_macro_stack_length:  Specifies  that  the  macro  stacking
                length should not be more than the specified value.

              * min_space_between_macro_stack:  Specifies  the spacing between
                different macro stacks.

              * <max_space_between_macros>: Specifies the  maximum  space  be-
                tween  macros.  When the macro spacing is less than the speci-
                fied value, the macros are counted in the stacking length. For
                example, if the max_space_between_macro value is  9  then  the
                macros  will  be considered as packed if the space between the
                macros is between 0 and 9, however, if the real  space  is  10
                then nothing will happened.

              Data_type: string, optional

Example
              * The   following  command creates a macro array, ram_array, and
                defines it constraints.

                set_macro_place_constraint          -array           ram_array
                {{ip1/dma/r0_irx:R0       4.66      ip1/dma/r1_irx:MY      8.0
                ip1/dma/r2_irx:MY}      2.33      {ip1/dma/r3_irx:R0      4.66
                ip1/dma/r_irx:MY}} -valid_group_orients {R0 MY}

